{"cursor":"53327","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\nIn computing, a 'mouse' is a pointing device that functions by detecting\ntwo-dimensional motion relative to its supporting surface. Physically, a\nmouse consists of an object held under one of the user's hands, with one or\nmore buttons.\n\nThe mouse sometimes features other elements, such as \"wheels\", which allow the\nuser to perform various system-dependent operations, or extra buttons or\nfeatures that can add more control or dimensional input. The mouse's motion\ntypically translates into the motion of a pointer on a display, which allows for\nfine control of a graphical user interface.\n","linknr":806,"url":"Computer_mouse","recorded":1362675477,"links":120,"instances":["computing","company","and_singulars_of_headless_nouns","computing","software","computing","computer_engineer","graphical_user_interfaces","gui","web_design","mechanics","computer_system","a9m0050"],"pdf":["http://memex.org/licklider.pdf","http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/Xplore/login.jsp?url=/iel5/7568/20620/00953558.pdf","http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/Xplore/login.jsp?url=/iel5/7568/20620/00953558.pdf"],"categories":["Pointing devices","Computing input devices","History of human–computer interaction","Video game control methods","American inventions","1964 introductions"],"headings":["Naming","Early mice","Variants","Connectivity and communication protocols","Operation","Multiple-mouse systems","Buttons","Mouse speed","Mousepads","In the marketplace","Use in games","See also","References","Further reading"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/aa/3-Tastenmaus_Microsoft.jpg/233px-3-Tastenmaus_Microsoft.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ed/Mouse-patents-englebart-rid.png/220px-Mouse-patents-englebart-rid.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wik